[3
Date: Tue, 26 Jan 1999 20:33:47 -0200
From: Claudio Maierovitch Pessanha Henriques <claudiomph@uol.com.br>
Subject: Coral Reef Kills and Potential Human Disease
A few years ago I could not find scientific studies demonstrating the
transmission of disease to humans by swimming or bathing in the sea.
There was a very illustrative Article(Shuval, H.I. - The Case for
Microbial Standards for Bathing Beaches, in International Discharge of
Sewage from Sea Outfalls Symposium. Oxford: Pergamon Press, 1975 pp.
95-101) that estimated the amount of sea water accidentally swallowed
and that could be crossed with the concentration of pathogenic
microorganisms necessary for sickness. Of course that source of
contamination is reasonable, but it is very hard to isolate it from
eating sea food or getting upper respiratory tract infections during
summer vacations at the beach. Otherwise, This polemic issue must not
shadow the meaning of fighting for high quality water patterns.
--
Claudio Maierovitch Pessanha Henriques
<claudiomph@uol.com.br>
